               <history>
                  <origin>Possibly completed in either <origPlace cert="medium"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000231" key="place_7000231">Greater
                        Iran</origPlace> or the <origPlace cert="medium"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace> undated, but probably <origDate cert="medium"
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1600" notAfter="1700">17th century
                        CE</origDate>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased for 40 rupees by <persName role="fmo ato ins"
                           key="person_36969078" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/36969078/">Alexander Dow
                           (ca. 1730–1779)</persName> on <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                           when="1764-11-20">20 Nov. 1764</date> in <placeName type="city"
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001509" key="place_7001509">Benares
                           (Varanasi)</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Dow's death at Bhagalpur, his survivors inherited and then
                        sold his manuscript collection; however, where and when that occurred and
                        whether he or they brought the volume to Britain remains
                     unclear.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/300287774" key="person_300287774">Nathaniel
                           Middleton (1750-1807)</persName>, as per his bookplate on the <locus
                           from="Inner_back_cover" to="Inner_back_cover">left
                     pastedown</locus>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Middleton's death, his survivors inherited and sold his
                        manuscripts through the <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> firm of <persName role="auc" key="person_89854013"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/89854013/">James Christie Jr
                           (1773–1831)</persName> where bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           key="person_284795376" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/284795376">William
                           Baynes (fl. 1792–1841)</persName> purchased it for £1 8 shillings.
                  </p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Probably purchased from Baynes by his friend, Methodist minister <persName role="fmo ins" key="person_120696480"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/120696480/">Rev. Adam Clarke
                           (1762–1832)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Clarke's death, his son <persName role="fmo"
                           key="person_79253656" ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/79253656/">Jospeh
                           Butterworth Bulmer Clarke (d. 1855)</persName> inherited the volume and
                        describes its present state in a catalogue published in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1835">1835</date>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>The next year on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1836-06-20">20
                           June 1836</date>, Clarke's son auctioned his father's collection through
                        the <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781">London</placeName> firm of <persName role="auc"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/133731879" key="person_133731879">Sotheby &amp;
                           Son</persName> where bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/person_12230379" key="person_12230379">John
                           Cochran</persName> purchased it for £2 4 shillings.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Probably sold by Cochran to scholar <persName
                           type="standard" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/"
                           key="person_20108923" role="fmo">Nathaniel Bland
                        (1803-1865)</persName> for his library at Randalls Park, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011735" key="place_7011735"
                           >Leatherhead</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>After Bland's death, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781" key="place_7011781"
                           >London</placeName> bookseller <persName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"
                           >Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866">1866</date>, and moved to <orgName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/295427552" key="person_295427552">Bibliotheca
                           Lindesiana</orgName> at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
